<div id="review_28697125" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/28697125" />
    <a title="Kerry" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/108491-kerry"><img alt="Kerry" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1203915585p2/108491.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/28697125?book_show_action=true">Jul 29, 2008</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Kerry" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Kerry" href="/user/show/108491-kerry">Kerry</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer28697125" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6919066249507735644">I really enjoyed the different voices in this book. The story is interesting and really puts in perspective what it is like to live under and ever shifting government as a child, businessman, and a mother in Iran. What if your values don&apos;t conform with those of the ruling elite? How do you come to terms with that? Or even survive? What can a child do? <br/><br/>My one complaint is that the book didn&apos;t go on long enough. There were a few issues that I wanted to hear more about. I especially wanted to hear </span>
  <span id="freeText6919066249507735644" style="display:none">I really enjoyed the different voices in this book. The story is interesting and really puts in perspective what it is like to live under and ever shifting government as a child, businessman, and a mother in Iran. What if your values don't conform with those of the ruling elite? How do you come to terms with that? Or even survive? What can a child do? <br /><br />My one complaint is that the book didn't go on long enough. There were a few issues that I wanted to hear more about. I especially wanted to hear the son and daughter's thoughts a bit more. Certainly an interesting read.<br /> <br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="6919066249507735644" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

