<div id="review_1410324562" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1410324562" />
    <a title="Elizabeth" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/622596-elizabeth"><img alt="Elizabeth" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1439596006p2/622596.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1410324562?book_show_action=true">Oct 06, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Elizabeth" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Elizabeth" href="/user/show/622596-elizabeth">Elizabeth</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1410324562" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5372970426401296654">This is a gorgeous and captivating semi-autobiographical read that follows a Jewish family of four through the fall of the Shah in Iran and the ensuing revolution. Through a crackdown on wealthy citizens and an imposed moral code, Isaac Amin, a self-made successful gemologist and socialite, is imprisoned and held without charges. The period of imprisonment is narrated by all four family members: Farnaz, the housewife and world traveler with expensive taste but a big heart, Shirin an intrepid nin</span>
  <span id="freeText5372970426401296654" style="display:none">This is a gorgeous and captivating semi-autobiographical read that follows a Jewish family of four through the fall of the Shah in Iran and the ensuing revolution. Through a crackdown on wealthy citizens and an imposed moral code, Isaac Amin, a self-made successful gemologist and socialite, is imprisoned and held without charges. The period of imprisonment is narrated by all four family members: Farnaz, the housewife and world traveler with expensive taste but a big heart, Shirin an intrepid nine year old for whom the revolution removes the magic of her childhood, and Parviz, an emigrant and beginning of the diaspora reconciling his lost life in a vast and cold New York. These perspectives successfully illuminate the multifaceted impact of the Fall. Sofer's account is beautifully organized, and her writing style allows the reader to immerse in Iranian day-to-day life both before and after the revolution. The pacing lent itself to lofty and heartbreaking ruminations on family, personal aspirations, identity, and personal values. Certainly recommended.</span>
  <a data-text-id="5372970426401296654" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


