    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1507748887" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1507748887" />
    <a title="Angie Fehl" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/10093055-angie-fehl"><img alt="Angie Fehl" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1339212803p2/10093055.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1507748887?book_show_action=true">Jan 12, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Angie Fehl" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Angie Fehl" href="/user/show/10093055-angie-fehl">Angie Fehl</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780061130410" href="/book/show/2061362.The_Septembers_of_Shiraz">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1507748887" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1095522043326245743">3.5 Stars<br/><br/><br/>It opens in September (obvs) 1981, during the Iranian Revolution. Isaac Amin, an Iranian rare gems dealer living in Tehran, finds himself surrounded by police one day at work. They notify him that he is under arrest for being a possible government spy. Yeah, they don&apos;t even have any solid proof at this point, but they make it clear it doesn&apos;t matter. He&apos;s immediately hauled off to prison, his wife casually notified of the whole scene some time later, when she has to go seek out herself </span>
  <span id="freeText1095522043326245743" style="display:none">3.5 Stars<br /><br /><br />It opens in September (obvs) 1981, during the Iranian Revolution. Isaac Amin, an Iranian rare gems dealer living in Tehran, finds himself surrounded by police one day at work. They notify him that he is under arrest for being a possible government spy. Yeah, they don't even have any solid proof at this point, but they make it clear it doesn't matter. He's immediately hauled off to prison, his wife casually notified of the whole scene some time later, when she has to go seek out herself why her husband didn't come home from work. While the details of the whys and hows of Isaac's imprisonment are left murky for much of the story, what does come to light are all the other secrets within Isaac's marriage and family life, mainly the fact that the family is secretly Jewish in a primarily Muslim community. <br /><br />But it's not just Isaac's perspective we get to know. In fact, the chapters alternate between Isaac, his wife, Farnaz, who remains in the family home with 9 year old daughter Shirin, and Isaac's grown son Parvis living in a Hassidic Jewish community while studying architecture in New York City. There are quite a few minor characters who also get brief storylines, sometimes making it difficult to keep track of who is who while reading. <br /><br />One of the most stand-out elements to this novel is the poignancy behind the scenes, especially when experienced through the inner monologue of Isaac as he contemplates his situation in prison, and the men he gets to know while he is there. I found the analogy of life to the game of Monopoly especially powerful -- how Isaac thinks on how you can do everything right in life and still land in jail. He also thinks on how he witnesses fellow Iranians being imprisoned, tortured, even executed for what essentially comes to being in the wrong place at the wrong time or just having an unfortunate family / friend connection that you can't help. One fellow prisoner comments that while he sits in prison he also has his three daughters in another part of prison, "one for being a communist, one for being an adulteress, and one for being their sister."<br /><br />When the plot is not pointing at the political or religious climate of the era, it focuses more on the struggles within Isaac &amp; Farnaz's marriage. As it turns out, they had been having struggles for some time, trying to work their way back from an unintentional distancing over the years, wanting to figure out how to reconnect. They had been making solid progress and even had a date night planned on the night of Isaac's capture. Being left alone in the home as Isaac sits in prison, Farnaz has her own inner thoughts running, at times questioning if she made a mistake choosing Isaac as her mate, other times angry at him, internally accusing him for not being the man who initially won her heart, his romantic side getting lost in his obsession to keep his family financially comfortable. But she also finds herself scared, fearing that she might never again get the chance to tell him everything sitting in her heart, the joys and loves as well as the hurts.<br /><br />Author Dalia Sofer mentions in her afterword that she was around the age of Isaac's daughter in the story when she herself had to flee Iran with her family, moving to the U.S. Sofer reveals that the character of Isaac was built around what she heard of her own father's experiences in an Iranian prison. <br /><br />I was really impressed with the story, the themes it addresses and the poetic, touching way Sofer crafts emotionally difficult scenes. Because there were certain scenes in the story that were highly graphic in violence, there was painful imagery created in my mind that has me unsure if I'd ever be able to read this book again, though I am most glad to have experienced it at least once and look forward to delving into more of Sofer's works in the future!</span>
  <a data-text-id="1095522043326245743" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

