        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer931620195" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6692331311536079262">I finally got around to reading this book (copyright 2007). I thought it was well written. I really got caught up in Isaac Amin and his family&apos;s story. Let&apos;s just say, I couldn&apos;t put it down. I constantly asked myself, what if this were happening to my family? What would I do? I can&apos;t imagine being so scared of your every move or the possibility of being turned in by your neighbors or co-workers, to be questioned about your daily life activities, to be charged, tortured and executed because of y</span>
  <span id="freeText6692331311536079262" style="display:none">I finally got around to reading this book (copyright 2007). I thought it was well written. I really got caught up in Isaac Amin and his family's story. Let's just say, I couldn't put it down. I constantly asked myself, what if this were happening to my family? What would I do? I can't imagine being so scared of your every move or the possibility of being turned in by your neighbors or co-workers, to be questioned about your daily life activities, to be charged, tortured and executed because of your associations, beliefs, successes and status. This is what Isaac and his Iranian Jewish family must face in the aftermath of the fall of the Shah and the rise of Iran's Revolutionary Guards. Highly recommend reading this book, if you haven't already.<br><br>Note: This was a book that I received from a member at <br><a href="http://www.bookcrossing.com" rel="nofollow noopener">Bookcrossing.com</a><br><br>
  
  
  
  
  
  <img src="https://images.gr-assets.com/hostedimages/1380388898ra/749754.gif" width="468" height="60" class="gr-hostedUserImg">
 <br><br></span>
