<div id="review_32252391" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/32252391" />
    <a title="Marcy prager" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1140398-marcy-prager"><img alt="Marcy prager" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1209997030p2/1140398.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/32252391?book_show_action=true">Sep 07, 2008</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Marcy prager" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Marcy prager" href="/user/show/1140398-marcy-prager">Marcy prager</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>


          <div><span class="uitext greyText">Recommends it for: </span>
           <span class="uitext reviewText">everyone!</span></div>

          <div>
    <span class="greyText">Recommended to Marcy prager by: </span>
      Amazon.com
  </div>


    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer32252391" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14909164659971409212">I was engrossed immediately in the drama of a missing Jewish gem dealer named Isaac who had been abducted in Tehran, Iran on the heels of the Iranian revolution, accused of being an Zionist spy. For months on end, Isaac lived his life in prison, tortured and beaten. His wife and daughter await his return, not at all sure if he will return. From riches to rags, Isaac rehashes his life in prison with his wife, his son, who lives in N.Y. City, his daughter, his abusive and alcoholic father, and his</span>
  <span id="freeText14909164659971409212" style="display:none">I was engrossed immediately in the drama of a missing Jewish gem dealer named Isaac who had been abducted in Tehran, Iran on the heels of the Iranian revolution, accused of being an Zionist spy. For months on end, Isaac lived his life in prison, tortured and beaten. His wife and daughter await his return, not at all sure if he will return. From riches to rags, Isaac rehashes his life in prison with his wife, his son, who lives in N.Y. City, his daughter, his abusive and alcoholic father, and his association with the shah. Isaac retains his "cool" with his interrogator and compassion for his cell mates when he is not in solitary confinement. He hears the shots and acknowledges the deaths of those he knows and has met in prison. Isaac is caught in between resignation and hope that he will rejoin his family. In other chapters, Isaac's son, wife, brother, and daughter relive their memories with their father, living in between despair that their father will be killed, and hope that he will return. In the name of revolution, lives are turned upside down. The poor resent the rich, and many hope and work for their demise. Dalia Sofer, the writer, was born in Iran and fled at the age of ten to the United States with her family. Much of this story, are her memories...</span>
  <a data-text-id="14909164659971409212" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


